SIMPLE: portraiture
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Portraiture
<hw>Por"trai*ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>portraiture</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A portrait; a likeness;
a painted resemblance; hence, that which is copied from some example or
model.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For, by the image of my cause, I see⟦br⟧
The <qex>portraiture</qex> of his.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Divinity maketh the love of ourselves the pattern; the love of our
neighbors but the <qex>portraiture</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pictures, collectively; painting.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The art or practice of making portraits.</def>
<rj><au>Walpole.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Portraiture</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Portraiture
<hw>Por"trai*ture</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To represent by a
portrait, or as by a portrait; to portray.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shaftesbury.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Portray</ent>⟦br⟧
